The paper deals with distributed/parallel algorithms for processing large-scale graphs, which falls under the category of distributed computing (cs.DC). The algorithms are designed for computing spanners and distance approximation, which are fundamental graph problems and fall under the category of graph theory (cs.DS). The paper also discusses the massively parallel computation (MPC) model, which is a widely-adopted theoretical abstraction of MapReduce style settings, and falls under the category of distributed systems (cs.Distributed). The algorithms are designed to work in the strongly sublinear regime of local memory, which falls under the category of memory hierarchy (cs.DM). Finally, the paper discusses the application of the algorithms to all pairs shortest path (APSP), which is a problem in network analysis (cs.NE).
